comments.body:
> Physical Location (can this be pulled from the collection-level note?) | 982
> -- | --

Can you provide a little more information about this? 

The collection is split between two locations, both of which are reflected on the collection level--so pulling the location from the collection level for the item-level bib records doesn't make sense to me. We can pull it from the linked container record for each object.

Do you want the location in a bib 982? Do you want a holdings record created? Again, a MARC example would be helpful.

> . | .
> -- | -- 
> Agent/Creator/Persname or Famname | 100
> Agent/Creator/Corpname | 110
> Agent/Subject | 600 
> Agent/Creator | 700 

Can you elaborate on this please? 
* Do you want a 6xx + 7xx for any creator? Or do you only want the 600 / 700 (i.e. personal names)? 
* Do you want the 6xx / 7xx when the agent is linked with the corresponding role in ASpace, or are you asking that we construct the 6xx / 7xx?

> > Physical Location (can this be pulled from the collection-level note?)
> > 982
> 
> Can you provide a little more information about this?
> 
> The collection is split between two locations, both of which are reflected on the collection level--so pulling the location from the collection level for the item-level bib records doesn't make sense to me. We can pull it from the linked container record for each object.
> 
> Do you want the location in a bib 982? Do you want a holdings record created? Again, a MARC example would be helpful.

Pulling the info from the linked container record makes sense to me. (I think there's a ticket to have this happen at the collection level as well.) 

Do we need physical location to be added to bib 982 if that info is in the holdings record? The only reason we thought a bib 982 was needed is because this is in included in collection-level MARC records. On the flip slide, should we have this information only in bib 982 and not create a holdings record since we don't want users to be able to request items from the catalog? Is a holdings record required?

Yes, sorry, we would like a 6xx + 7xx for any creator; and yes, the a 6xx + 7xx when the agent is linked with the corresponding role. Is that right, @LynnDurgin?

I tried to create a sample MARC record from the mapping we did: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1iSgOT3CMJBo7_BacrJz7udJOywNAPNlDTihssWNZ1Pw/edit. Is this helpful/what you're looking for @regineheberlein?

figgy.title: Raster / Vector fileset manager doesnâ€™t display thumbnails

comments.body: yes this fixes it

I looked into this some. People say don't use `CGI.escape` because it doesn't do the right thing with spaces, but we're already stripping spaces in https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/blob/8ebd4efa4451169295ade1d924fe694b6d074aed/app/decorators/ephemera_term_decorator.rb#L45-L47 so I think that's fine.

However, it encodes commas as `%2C` which URI.escape did not. 

The uris here don't seem to resolve. I'm not sure how important it is that they be identical before and after this change.

the tests are
https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/blob/8ebd4efa4451169295ade1d924fe694b6d074aed/spec/decorators/ephemera_term_decorator_spec.rb#L29-L51
We (dpul) are the only consumers of this endpoint. We think CGI.escape is fine and can update the tests.
CI is passing here, but the reform-rails patch has me nervous about numismatics nested form validations, if there are any. We should QA.
We tested nested forms with the date range property and it validated fine.

comments.body:
I feel like I'm making fairly good progress on this by hewing pretty closely to the bibdata code. One place I'm confused right now is [local_identifier](https://github.com/pulibrary/bibdata/blob/e92ba310e4cc859a8b40494eee018f5e06156eb2/app/models/jsonld_record.rb#L139). 

From my reading of the code, it looks like it's 
- only displaying cicognara numbers 
  - This is especially confusing because I don't think those identifiers are local?
- local_identifier doesn't seem to be included in https://bibdata.princeton.edu/context.json, which I would expect.

In addition, I can't seem to find any examples of works with cicognara numbers in the catalog, although that may just be because I don't know how to search for them correctly.
@tpendragon - the above may be a question for you?

orangelight.title: Add jsonld as option for record export

comments.body:
There are three values that I'm not sure about
- local_identifier (currently not implemented)
  - From my reading of the code, bibdata is only displaying cicognara numbers 
  - I can't find an example of a record that uses these, and cicognara numbers don't seem like local_identifiers
  - local_identifier isn't included in https://bibdata.princeton.edu/context.json 
- identifier
  - It looks like the bibdata implementation is only displaying `iiif_manifest_paths`, so that's how I've implemented it here, but I'm not positive that is what's wanted 
- electronic_locations
  - Currently pulling from `electronic_access_1display` and displaying all of them - it does not appear that that's what's happening in bibdata - see, for example, `9946093213506421` https://bibdata.princeton.edu/bibliographic/9946093213506421/jsonld vs the "with a digitized manuscript" example in the tests on this branch.
This May help with this ticket: https://github.com/pulibrary/pdc_describe/blob/main/spec/models/doi_spec.rb#L30-L45
